25|$|A 2009 reform, {{effective}} on 1 March 2010, enables parties to a lawsuit or trial {{to question the}} constitutionality of the law that is being applied to them. The procedure, known as question <b>prioritaire</b> de constitutionnalité, is broadly as follows: the question is raised before the trial judge and, if it has merit, it is forwarded to the appropriate supreme court (Council of State if the referral comes from an administrative court, Cour de Cassation for other courts). The supreme court collects such referrals and submits them to the Constitutional Council. If the Constitutional Council rules a law to be unconstitutional, this law is struck down from the law books; this decision is valid for everybody and not only for the cases at hand.|$|E
